<h1> Coupling from the past (CFTP)</h1>



<h4>Trouble with MCMC</h4>

MCMC suffers from one great problem, viz, choice of the
length of the chain. Unless we have good ways to check convergence the
distribution that we get may be a poor approximation to the target
distribution. One way to remedy this is by using CFTP. The basic idea is
as follows.

<p>Run more than one version of the chain in parallel. Based on
their relative
behaviour decide when to stop.
Thus, instead of running the chain for a
prespecified length, here we run it until a stopping time.
This is again our familiar sequential
sampling idea. 



<h4>MC from another perspective</h4>

Propp-Wilson algorithm works only for finite sample space. There are
generalisations for infinite cases, that we shall not go into. 
A MC on a
finite sample space S is essentially determined by a transition
matrix. (We do not care about the initial distribution here.)
This is the traditional view of MC. Here we shall introduce
another approach: random map view. 

<p>In this view we have a bunch of maps from S to S. Call these as


<blockquote>
f<sub>1</sub>,...,f<sub>N</sub>,
</blockquote>


and attach probabilities 


<blockquote>
p<sub>1</sub>,...,p<sub>N</sub>
</blockquote>


to them. p<sub>i</sub>'s add up to 1. Now, our
step is made as follows. Suppose that we are at x. Pick one of the N maps
at random, say, f<sub>i</sub> with probability p<sub>i</sub>.
Then move to f<sub>i</sub>(x). 

<p>

<table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#995555"></td>
<td>
<b>Example:</b> 
 Consider the simple symmetric random walk modulo 7.
<table border="0" align=left>
<tr><td><img src="image/circ7.gif">
<td width=50></table>
 Here n=7. We consider
only two maps (ie, N=2 here): f<sub>1</sub>(x) = x+1 (mod 7) and
f<sub>2</sub>(x) = x-1 (mod 7). Each has prob 
0.5.
</td></tr></table>
</blockquote>



<p>

<table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#995555"></td>
<td>
<b>Example:</b> 
 In Ludo we have 6 maps of the form "advance i steps"
i=1,...,6. Each roll of die chooses one of these and applies it to the
present state. 

</td></tr></table>
</blockquote>

<p>

<table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#995555"></td>
<td>
<b>Example:</b> 
Consider S={1,2}. We shall work with 4 maps:  

<blockquote>

f<sub>1</sub>(1) = 1 f<sub>1</sub>(2) = 1<br>
f<sub>2</sub>(1) = 2 f<sub>2</sub>(2) = 2<br>
f<sub>3</sub>(1) = 1 f<sub>3</sub>(2) = 2<br>
f<sub>4</sub>(1) = 2 f<sub>4</sub>(2) = 1

</blockquote>

We attach prob 1/6, 1/3, 1/3, 1/6, respectively, to these. Check that the
transition matrix is
<blockquote>
<pre>
1/2 1/2
1/3 2/3
</pre>
</blockquote>

</td></tr></table>
</blockquote>



<table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#995555"></td>
<td>
<b>Example:</b> 
Computer scientists are
fond of the random map view of MCs. 
Here is a simple but interesting example. Our state space
is <b>R</b><sup>2</sup>. So each X<sub>i</sub> is a point in the plane. We
move from X<sub>i</sub> to X<sub>i+1</sub> as follows. 

<p>There are 4 functions f<sub>k</sub> from
<b>R</b><sup>2</sup>
to  <b>R</b><sup>2</sup> of the form 

<blockquote>
f<sub>k</sub>(x) = A<sub>k</sub> x + b<sub>k</sub>,
</blockquote>

where A<sub>k</sub>'s are known 2x2 matrices and b<sub>k</sub>'s are
known 2x1 vectors. Each f<sub>k</sub> has a probability p<sub>k</sub>
attached with it (sum(p<sub>k</sub>) = 1). To move from  X<sub>i</sub> to
X<sub>i+1</sub> we pick one of the f<sub>k</sub>'s at random (with
probability p<sub>k</sub>) and move to f<sub>k</sub>(X<sub>i</sub>), ie, 

<blockquote>
X<sub>i+1</sub> = f<sub>k</sub>(X<sub>i</sub>).
</blockquote>


<p>
These MC's are very useful for data compression. To see how, download this
little <a href="ifs.m">Matlab code</a> and run it. All that it does
is to run a MC (the A's and b's are given in the Matlab code) for 10000
steps and plots all the 10000 X's. Is the resulting picture familiar? Here
the 4 A's and b's store the picture in a compressed form. 
</td></tr></table>
</blockquote>


<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise PW.1:</font></b> 
   
   Show that given finite MC, there is at least one set of random maps for it.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   


<h4>Coupling</h4>

Suppose that we run two instances of the same MC. For instance, when two
players play a game of Ludo, their counters are two realisations of the same
MC. Now consider the random map view discussed above. Let both the MCs
always use the same random map (they may have different initial
distributions). Then we say that the MCs are <i>coupled.</i> Suppose they
start at X<sub>0</sub> and Y<sub>0</sub>, respectively. Then we pick one
of the maps randomly, say f<sub>i1</sub>. The MCs move to X<sub>1</sub> = 
f<sub>i1</sub>(X<sub>0</sub>) and Y<sub>1</sub> =
f<sub>i1</sub>(Y<sub>0</sub>), respectively. Then we pick a random map
f<sub>i2</sub>, say, and move to X<sub>2</sub> = 
f<sub>i2</sub>(X<sub>1</sub>) and Y<sub>2</sub> =
f<sub>i2</sub>(Y<sub>1</sub>), and so on. 
<p>
Similarly, we can run any number of MCs in a coupled way.
Notice that the trajectories of coupled MCs 
may look quite different. However, if the chains happen to hit a
common state at some time point, then they would continue together ever
afterward.  


<p><center>
<img src="resources/statinf2/pw2.gif">
</center><p>


In this case we say that the two coupled MCs have <i>coalesced.</i> The
first time (T) they meet is called the <i>coalescence point.</i> Note that
in general coalescence may never take place.




<h4>Forward coupling until coalescence</h4>

Suppose that our state space is of size K, and our MC is irreducible and
aperiodic. So we have unique limiting distribution &pi;. 
 We run K coupled versions of the
MC, one version starting from each state. We show a set of typical
trajectories for state space S = {1,2,3,4,5,6}.


<p><center>
<img src="resources/statinf2/pwall.gif">
</center><p>


In this picture we have coalescence at time T. The coalescence state is
s. However, it is <i>not</i> true in general that all these coupled MC's has to
eventually coalesce. In this note we shall call a set of random maps (ie,
some f<sub>i</sub>'s and their corresponding p<sub>i</sub>'s) as
irreducible and aperiodic, if the MC they generate is so. We shall call an
irreducible and aperiodic set of random maps as <i>surely coalescent</i>
if all the coupled versions (one version starting at each state) must
eventually coalesce, as in the above diagram. 

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise PW.2:</font></b> 
   
   Show that a set of random maps is surely coalescent if and only if there
   is a finite sequence F<sub>1</sub>,...,F<sub>a</sub> of these such that 
   
   <blockquote>
   F<sub>1</sub>#...#F<sub>a</sub> = some constant map.
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise PW.3:</font></b> 
   
   Show that it is possible to have an irreducible and aperiodic set of
   random maps that is not surely coalescent.<br>
                                                 <i>[Hint:
                                                 
                                                 We have already seen an example of this!
                                                 ]
                                                 </i>
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   


<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise PW.4:</font></b> 
   
   Consider simple symmetric random walk on the vertices of a
   triangle. One possible set of random maps is {f<sub>1</sub>,f<sub>2</sub>}
   each with probability 0.5, where f<sub>1</sub>(x) = x+1 mod 3, and
   f<sub>2</sub>(x) = x-1 mod 3. However, this set is not surely coalescent (why?)
   Obtain a set of surely coalescent random maps for this MC.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

Generalize this argument to get the following result.

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise PW.5:</font></b> 
   
   Consider any irreducible and aperiodic MC. Show that we can
   <i>always choose</i> a surely coalescent set of random maps for it.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   



<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise PW.6:</font></b> 
   
   Get a counterexample to show that the coalescence state need not be
   distributed according to  
   &pi;.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
Forward couping until coalescence  can be expressed mathematically as
follows. Let F<sub>1</sub>,F<sub>2</sub>,... be iid from the
f<sub>i</sub>'s according to probabilities p<sub>i</sub>'s. Write the
state space as {1,2,...,K}. Then the i-th
chain is 

<blockquote>
i, F<sub>1</sub>(i), F<sub>2</sub>(F<sub>1</sub>(i)),...
</blockquote>

Coalescence at step T means that the map

<blockquote>
F<sub>T</sub>#...#F<sub>1</sub>
</blockquote>

is a constant map. Here # is the function composition operator. In other
words, we can say that we are running a <i>function-valued</i> MC 

<blockquote>
ID, F<sub>1</sub>, F<sub>2</sub>#F<sub>1</sub>, 
F<sub>3</sub>F<sub>2</sub>F<sub>1</sub>,...,
</blockquote>

until the map becomes a constant map.

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#995555"></td>
   <td>
   <b>Example:</b> 
   
   Consider the 2-state MC again. 
   We shall denote a map from
   S to S by a vector of length 2, eg, [a b] denotes the function f where
   f(1) = a and f(2)=b. The map will be a constant map if a=b. Thus, there
   are two constant maps [1 1] and [2 2].
   <p>We start by generating an iid sequence of maps:
   F<sub>1</sub>,F<sub>2</sub>,...
   Suppose that these turn out as follows
   
   <blockquote>
   F<sub>1</sub> = [2 1], F<sub>2</sub> = [1 1], F<sub>3</sub> = [1
   2], F<sub>4</sub> = [2 1], ...
   </blockquote>
   
   Then our function-valued MC is
   
   <blockquote>
   ID=[1 2], [2 1]#[1 2]=[2 1], 
   <font color="#ff0000">[1 1]#[2 1] = [1 1], [1 2]#[1 1] =
   [2 2],...</font>.
   </blockquote>
   
   The red part shows the chain after coalescence. Note that the map always
   constant after coalescence, but sometimes it is [1 1] and sometimes [2 2].
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   


<h4>Backward coupling until coalescence</h4>

Propp-Wilson introduced a new use of coupling, namely, backward coupling
or coupling from the past (CFTP), for which the coalescence state is
indeed distributed as &pi;. <p>
Here also we assume that F<sub>1</sub>,F<sub>2</sub>,... be iid from the
f<sub>i</sub>'s according to probabilities p<sub>i</sub>'s. But now we
shall compose the F<sub>i</sub>'s in the <i>reverse</i> order to get the
function-valued MC

<blockquote>
ID, F<sub>1</sub>, F<sub>1</sub>#F<sub>2</sub>, 
F<sub>1</sub>F<sub>2</sub>F<sub>3</sub>,...
</blockquote>

and run it until the map becomes a constant map. Due to a reason that we
shall explain a bit later, this is called <i>coupling from the past
(CFTP).</i> Note that unlike forward coupling, the chain 

<blockquote>
X<sub>0</sub>,
F<sub>1</sub>(X<sub>0</sub>),F<sub>1</sub>F<sub>2</sub>(X<sub>0</sub>),...,
F<sub>1</sub>#...#F<sub>n</sub>(X<sub>0</sub>),...
</blockquote>
 
need not be a MC. However,

<blockquote>
ID, F<sub>1</sub>,
F<sub>1</sub>#F<sub>2</sub>,F<sub>1</sub>#F<sub>2</sub>#F<sub>3</sub>,...
</blockquote>

is a function-values MC.
<p>
Note that like forward coupling, here also the map remains a constant map
ever since coalescence. But unlike forward coupling, here it is the same
constant map. This is shown in the example below.

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#995555"></td>
   <td>
   <b>Example:</b> 
   
   Consider the same 2-state MC again, and the same F<sub>i</sub>'s.
   Now the MC is
   
   <blockquote>
   ID=[1 2], [1 2]#[2 1]=[2 1],
   <font color="#ff0000">[2 1]#[1 1] =
   [2 2], [2 2]#[1 2] = 
   [2 2],...</font>.
   </blockquote>
   
   Now after coalescence the map is always [2 2]. 
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise PW.7:</font></b> 
   
   Show that even for backward coupling, the same condition for sure
   coalescence holds: a set of random maps is surely coalescent (under
   backward coupling) iff there is a finite sequence of the maps whose
   composition is a constant map.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<h3>Basic Propp-Wilson (PW) algo</h3> 
Suppose that we are given an irreducible and aperiodic MC, and a surely
coalescent set of random maps for it. Let &pi; be the unique limiting
distribution for the MC. Then the PW algorithm generates from &pi; as
follows. 
<p>
Let the size of the state space be K. 
The algorithm runs K backward coupled versions of the MC with one version
starting from each state. The algorithm   stops at coalescence (which
surely occurs eventually), and outputs the
coalescent state.
<p>
It need not be at all obvious why the coalescence should ever occur, and
why  the coalescent state is indeed
distributed as &pi;. Also, the algorithm as stated looks quite messy,
since in practice K may be very large (as in the Gibbs example) and then
running the K MC's in parallel is a difficult job. We shall see how to get
rid of the computational burden later. For now let us prove that the
algorithm is correct, ie, the output is indeed distribute as &pi;.
First notice that if X is any S-valued random variable (S is our state
space), then showing that X has distribution &pi; is same as showing
that F<sub>1</sub>(X) has same distribution as X, where F<sub>1</sub> is a
<i>random</i> map drawn from the given set of random maps.

Define
(for nonnegative integers i &lt; j), 

<blockquote>
F<sub>i,j</sub> = F<sub>i</sub>#...#F<sub>j</sub>,
</blockquote>

where the F<sub>k</sub>'s are iid as before. Then clearly

<blockquote>
F<sub>i,j</sub> has same distribution as F<sub>k,l</sub>,
</blockquote>

if j-i = l-k.

Notice that, since the set of random maps we have started with is a surely
coalescent 
one, we must have

<blockquote>
F<sub>1,j</sub> = constant map eventually.
</blockquote>



<p>
Also, if F<sub>1,j</sub> is a constant map, then for all k 
                                                           <img src=
                                                           "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                                                           align=top>
                                                           
                                                            j, we
have F<sub>1,k</sub> = F<sub>1,j</sub>. We shall call this constant map as
F<sub>1,*</sub>. Note that it is just a random state, and is the output of
the algorithm. 

Similarly, we can define F<sub>2,*</sub>. Notice that
F<sub>2,*</sub> has same distribution as F<sub>1,*</sub>,
and 

<blockquote>
F<sub>1,*</sub> = F<sub>1</sub>#F<sub>2,*</sub>.
</blockquote>


These two things together prove that F<sub>1,*</sub> is indeed distributed
as &pi;. 


